BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Clay Exploration Evenings: Lvl 2 — Sebastopol Center For the Art
 s\, California
DTSTART:20260430T000000
DTEND:20260501T000000
UID:bc5a1646fdb0417e5bea2ee73e0d60c6@sebarts.org
DESCRIPTION:Clay Exploration Evenings: Lvl 2\, 4/30\n\n  \n    \n      \n 
        \n          $255.00\n        \n      \n    \n  \n\nThursdays\, Apri
 l 30 - June 4\, 2026 (6 sessions) 6 - 8:30pm$210 + $45 clay fee (pre-regis
 tration required)This course is designed for students wishing to explore h
 and-building techniques at an intermediate to advanced level and delve dee
 per into refining their clay skills. Each session will start with a demons
 tration of a specific technique related to functional and/or decorative po
 ttery. Participants are invited to explore new ideas and to try pieces tha
 t might be of a more challenging nature. Some of what we can explore are f
 reeform coil pots\, soft slab work\, hard slab technique\, a variety of sc
 ulptural techniques and a sampling of the many stamping\, carving and text
 ural surface treatments on clay. We will investigate ways to use slips and
  glaze that will add color to the forms we create.About the Instructor: Mi
 chael Citrino has had a love affair with clay for over 50 years. After his
  college experience at California College of Arts and Crafts with Viola Fr
 ey and further work at Humboldt State University with Lew Merrick\, he ran
  a stained glass business for 18 years. Michael and his wife left for Turk
 ey in 1991 to teach in International Schools. For 26 years he taught K-12 
 art\, including Ceramics\, Drawing\, Photography\, Design and Sculpture at
  schools in six different countries. He started clay programs for High Sch
 ool and Middle School students at three of those schools. At four of these
  schools he offered after school and weekend ceramics sessions for teacher
 s and parents. Michael’s work ranges from the traditional to the experim
 ental and a wide swath in between. His approach to teaching is to help stu
 dents explore the playful nature of the clay room and nurture a love for t
 he possibilities that medium presents. \n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\
 n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n          \n            \n              \n 
