DESCRIPTION:Intro to Wheel Throwing with Naomi & Jack\, 5/21/26\n\n  \n   
  \n      \n        \n          $295.00\n        \n      \n    \n  \n\nThur
 sdays\, May 21 -June 25\, 2026\; 2-5pm (6 weeks)$250 + $45 Clay Fee (max 8
  students)This course is designed for students who are new to the potter
 ’s wheel and eager to discover the fundamentals of wheel throwing. With 
 an emphasis on core technique\, each session builds a solid foundation in 
 the essential skills of centering\, opening\, pulling up walls\, trimming 
 and glazing — the building blocks that every potter returns to again and
  again.Each class begins with a demonstration focused on one or more of th
 ese foundational techniques\, giving students a clear picture of the proce
 ss before getting their hands in the clay. From there\, students work at t
 heir own wheels with plenty of time to practice\, explore and develop thei
 r feel for the material. The goal is for each person to leave the course b
 eing able to make a thrown piece — a bowl\, a mug\, a vase — that is g
 enuinely their own\, shaped by their emerging skills and their personal se
 nse of what they love about pottery.With two teachers in the room\, there 
 is ample opportunity for individual attention and hands-on guidance at eve
 ry stage of the process. At the same time\, there is real joy in learning 
 alongside others — watching a classmate pull up a wall for the first tim
 e\, or seeing a finished glaze come out of the kiln — and that shared ex
 perience is very much a part of what makes this class special.No prior exp
 erience is necessary. All you need is curiosity and a willingness to get a
  little muddy.About the Instructors: Naomi Fuchs brings a deep love of cla
 y and a genuine passion for sharing the experience with others to everythi
 ng she does in the clay room. She believes that each pot is an opportunity
  to learn — about the nature of clay\, and about yourself. Naomi has bee
 n throwing on the wheel for four years\, and in that time the practice has
  become a grounding\, peaceful and creative part of her life that has deep
 ened her connection to art and making. Her warm\, encouraging approach cre
 ates a space where beginners feel supported as they find their footing at 
 the wheel and begin to discover what clay can do in their hands.In just on
 e year\, pottery has become one of Jack Harrison’s passions—a craft th
 at continues to humble him\, calm him\, and inspire him as he shapes both 
 the clay and his own journey. Throwing vases is what he does most\, but he
  is experienced in all areas of the wheel. Sharing his passion with others
  in the studio has allowed him to become part of a community that supports
  and challenges each other. As a mellow\, focused individual\, beginners w
 ill find comfort in learning from him.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n
